TRIP COMMENTS: After birding Bayfront Park in Pinole, Lory Poulson and I spend the rest of the afternoon at the Pinole Regional Shoreline. A few notes: The Osprey and PECO were on pilings just offshore from the southwest part of the park. The Black Oystercatchers--a total of six individual birds--were roosting on the old pilings east of the fishing pier, also the location of the terns. The COHA, an immature, was hunting in the west side of the park, flying from euc to euc. We got multiple good looks at the bird. The bluebirds were quite active. One male burst onto the trail halfway to the pier and subdued a Jerusalem cricket.

Howard King and I joined a handful of others in checking the shoreline of the Salton Sea between Obsidian Butte and the west end of Bowles Road.  Our primary target was an Ancient Murrelet that was found the previous day near the north end of Lack Road by visiting birder Steve Arlow.  We therefore spent much of our time off the north end of Lack Road and we concentrated our time here and elsewhere searching for the murrelet among the ducks and grebes along the shoreline and on the offshore waters.  I briefly scanned the pelican and cormorant flocks at Obsidian Butte and some of the gulls and shorebirds elsewhere, but we really did not look at landbirds at all (though we heard a few incidentally).  Also present was Jon Dunn, Martha Estus, Steve Arlow, and several others, and just as we were leaving, we encountered Tom Benson and Doug Karalun at Obsidian Butte.  It was clear and essentially calm, though at times with a trace (5 knot) breeze, and temperatures ranging from the low 60s to the low or mid-70s.  8:15-11:45 am.

Pat Bacchetti, Lory Poulson, and I joined Dede Sabbag''s team for the Southern Marin CBC, covering the marshes of Mill Valley and adjacent areas, beginning at the Mill Valley Sewage Treatment Plant. We walked from the plant south through the Bothin Marsh Open Space Preserve, detouring around the west side of the marsh and along the Coyote Creek Trail, and winding up just south of the 101 bridge over Richardson Bay. We worked our way north, ending at Bayfront Park, before covering two other areas. We tried but had no luck finding Clapper Rails. The Mew Gull count of 450 birds was more than I have ever seen. Another nice surprise was the two PEFA on the towers.

TRIP COMMENTS: On 9/12/09, I pedaled my bike to the Santa Ana River and rode from Katella to Imperial, thoroughly birding the riverbed the entire way. The river was completely dry almost to Lincoln, but from there upstream there was always at least one channel of shallow water in the riverbed. My main objective was to find a PESA or some other rare shorebird. Unfortunately, shorebirds were a bite scarce, and the only marginally interesting one I saw was two nice WISN near the Tustin crossing. Ducks are on the increase. Lots of dabblers, including my first wigeon of the fall. Two calling VIRA in some thick vegetation somewhere near Glassel were nice. One of the most interesting sightings of the day was a BTPI on a wire between Tustin and the I-91 crossing. I've never seen one on the river before. Passerine migrants weren't too common, though I did see MGWA, ATFL, WIWA, LAZB, etc. I ran into Doug Willick looking at shorebird flocks south of Imperial, where the most shorebirds were. We chatted and scanned the flocks for an hour or so, not seeing anything unusual. I left around 1:45, going home via the enormous hill on Imperial.

TRIP COMMENTS: I was actually here twice on this date, the first time from 1120 to 1145 hrs., and then 1400-1510 hrs. The first 25 minutes I was here in my own, while during the second time period I was here with Phil Brown, during which time we ran into Neil Gilbert, who was here to look for a Blackburnian Warbler I'd seen during the morning visit.  During this visit I didn't really look at the SAR (much), as most of my attention, which was limited in time, was focused on trees along the bike trail. I'd gotten a late start (I was supposed to meet Debbie and Phil, and Shirley, at the Orange Old-Towne Circle, to celebrate Debbie and Shirley's birthdays). But in the short time walking the trees (mainly the Chinese Elms) I was surprised by the number of warblers, and by the percentage of non-YRWAs. And of course just when it was time to leave, wouldn't you know it, I then run into the Blackburnian Warbler. So after the four of us had lunch at the "Circle" (and Debbie and Shirley had begin their "boutique" shopping, Phil and Inexcused ourselves and I took him back to the SAR to look for the warblers. While Neil was here looking for the Blackburnian, he had found a Baltimore Oriole, which none of us could refind. ----Weather (in general, for the day):  Clear, warm (mid 70°s and low 80°s F). Mild breezes (2-3 mph, SW).

TRIP COMMENTS: As predicted, the on-shore flow increased its influence overnight and the low clouds and fog layer extended further inland today. The fog disappeared pretty quickly (at least at the marsh), but the clouds persisted until Leo Ohtsuki and I were at Mason Regional Park at about 1030 or so. I looked at the “inside” ponds, of course, but mostly covered the “back 40” willow riparian areas, but also looked at most of the outer ponds (the old red-flowering euc row with myoporum understory at the northeast corner of the “L” shaped pond, but inside the water treatment plant, has been removed along with much of the existing vegetation inside the facility – what the hell?).

TRIP COMMENTS: SWBSC; 16 observers, 30 Nov 2009, 12:30PM-1:30PM, Clear, 75 deg F, calm winds 0-1 mph; Leader: Jim Hardesty. Parking lot and picnic area past entrance pond north to pond C and return.

High pressure has been in control for past few days with offshore winds and dry conditions. This Thanksgiving morning started on the cool side (48° F was predicted low for this morning in Huntington Beach) with calm and clear conditions, but quickly warmed up to the 70s. As I arrived, Canada Geese were overhead and calling. Clearly they are roosting here overnight as by about sun-up, most of them have departed to the northwest. It’s also clear that not all are roosting at this body of water, but are using another nearby spot (is it only Sully Miller Pond?). So how regular is this event? I assume they are foraging during the day at the Seal Beach Naval Weapons Station, but I also know that the flocks there are much larger than the numbers I’ve seen here. So where else do they forage? Why not roost at Anaheim Bay? Anyway, I recorded the following:

TRIP COMMENTS: The weather forecast for today, Saturday, was rain. The forecast was for intermittent light showers in the morning diminishing by late morning into the afternoon, before the next band of heavier showers arrives late in the day. Showers are expected to linger in the area through Sunday morning. I looked at Huntington Lake from 0630 to 0710 with my scope from under the porch at Alice’s Restaurant (apparently this “Breakfast in the Park” Café will close on Labor Day 2010 to be followed, it appears, by a bakery operated by the daughter of Alice Gustafson). I then started to walk around the lake to check on things such as the recent White-throated Sparrow reported by Jim Pike, but the rain became too much for me and I retreated to the car. There were some NRSW hanging out by the reed-bed at the southwest corner of the lake (roosting?). Jim had reported three, I think, but I saw at least five or six this morning (two wintered here last year – or was it four?). I then went to the east side of the park but never left my car due to rain and left shortly after 8 am.

Brian Daniels and I took a quick trip out to Lake Perris in search of a Red-throated Loon that was found here the previous weekend.  While here, we scanned the lake from parking lots 1 and 2 in search of the loon and whatever else we could find.  We also took a brief walk behind the parking lot in search of the Long-eared Owl that I found here on my last visit, but we were unable to locate either this bird or anything else of note.  We did see the loon, but it was in the middle of the lake where difficult to see well.  Although quite a few gulls were present, most were on the water well offshore, and thus largely too far away to identify with confidence.  It was partly cloudy, with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze from the west, and temperatures in the low 60s.  12:40-1:40 pm.----California Ground-Squirrel - 10.

LOCALITY: Coronado, US Naval Amphibious Base, Delta Beach
TRIP COMMENTS: Chet McGaugh, Mike San Miguel, John Green, and I joined a large group of people (including Guy McCaskie, Elizabeth Copper, Pete Ginsburg, Todd McGrath, Brian Daniels, Leo Ohtsuki, Terry Hunefield, in a search for a bird identified as a Great Knot.  We spent most of our time inside the fence at Delta Beach near the southern end of the Silver Strand, but some of us also worked along the bike trail outside the fence.  We did see the target bird briefly shortly after we arrived, but it soon disappeared and we never saw it again (though it was seen again after we left along the beach).  We therefore spent most of our time scanning the saltmarsh and waiting for the tide to recede enough for the birds to feed.  It was clear, with a mild breeze, and temperatures probably in the upper 70s.  3:20-6:30 pm.

TRIP COMMENTS: Rare species notes:--Observers included Peter Ginsburg and Stan Walens, among others.----Common Murre: large alcid with typical rapid steady wingbeat, black above, white below, with head held above body as it flew.----Ancient Murrelet: tiny alcid, with rapid wingbeat, white below, with obvious white extending up to the nape in front of the wings, wings dark grey (not black)----Buller''s Shearwater: distant bird obviously gleaming and completely white below through undertail coverts, long thin pointed wings, thinner than a Manx, upperside not seen well, but obviously NOT black, but appearing dark grey.  Bird was maing fairly high, graceful buoyant arcs as it flew.  Observed for about 5 minutes.

TRIP COMMENTS: Curtis caught up with me in this town on the south side of Morro Bay. There had been a White-winged Dove with the Eurasian Collared-Doves. It was seen near 4th Street a day or two ago. We wandered around the town looking for it, looked at the bay from 3rd Street and Elfin Forest overlooks, and looked at Mike Stiles’s backyard for a Red Fox Sparrow. The only highlights were three geese with coots at a pond on the Los Osos Golf Course.

What a fine is unspectacular morning for me, Peggy and Michelle Brodie.  The Kingbird and the Osprey were both year birds, and the overall mix of birds, while not containing hyper-rarities, certainly got the day off to a good start.  Mild, pleasant.

TRIP COMMENTS: Coverage: Jodi Brown and I were dropped by boat at a point (34.59580 -119.93999) deep north in Cachuma Bay; we were visiting this location as part of the annual Bald Eagle count conducted on the lake. We found that we could not move from our point very far so we looked and listened from within 50m of our point. Because the wind was calm for most of the period we could hear some bird sounds from across the channel. We counted nothing in the main lake or near the Cachuma Bay mouth. We used the imitations of Northern Pygmy-Owl to draw birds to us. Many detections were by voice. Original notes reside at the UC Santa Barbara Center for Biodiversity and Ecological Restoration Field Note Archive: Cachuma 10 Jan 09.pdfThis shows our position and the lake level in June 2009.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birded with Oscar Johnson.  We were also joined, briefly, by Ryan Terrill and Jill Gautreaux.----Circumstances: Matt Brady and I were checking a few sites in southern Santa Cruz County for gulls and stopped at the dump next to Harkin’s Slough, on western Harkin’s Slough Road. There was a high overcast and scattered light rain, which made birding a little difficult, but there were large numbers (~3000-4000) of gulls at the dump, as the workers were turning the solid waste with tractors, thus exposing much food. Matt and I spent some time scanning the flocks before checking the flock bathing in the slough, and then returning to the dump, as there was considerable turnover between birds flying to the south and between the dump and the slough. By this time we had found five Glaucous Gulls, and were feeling encouraged. When we returned to the dump, we spent a while looking through the birds there. Within about fifteen minutes I came across an odd-looking second cycle bird, and I called Matt over to look at it. It initially struck me as having characteristics of a Great Black-backed, albeit having a far too pale back and slight structure. Matt concurred that it looked odd, after a few minutes of studying the bird we came to the conclusion that it was a Lesser Black-backed, probably of the subspecies graellsi. We called a few local birders about the bird, and Ryan and Jill were able to come down from Santa Cruz to look for it. While they were on their way we watched the bird as it moved slowly amongst other gulls roosting on the closest hillside, still about  meters away. During this time we were able to get about 80-100 photos of the bird, although they were not of the best quality due to the distance. It eventually moved behind a ridge and we lost it, just a few minutes before Ryan and Jill arrived. We spent the next half hour or so trying to relocate the bird, unsuccessfully, before Matt and I had to return to Santa Cruz. Ryan and Jill saw the bird a little while later, but further away.
Birded with Oscar Johnson and Adam Searcy; we were unable to refind the putative Lesser Black-backed Gull Oscar and I saw yesterday.
